 <div2 class ="Chemistry"> <h3><u>Chemistry</u></h3></div2>
 <p3 class ="Chemistry"></p3>
 Chemistry is the study of matter's characteristics, behaviour, and structure. In all instruction in chemistry classes, our students gain a foundational understanding of chemistry, including chemical bonding, raidoactivity, and the characteristics of solids, liquids, and gases. We also learn all about atoms, ions, and molecules, which make up elements and compounds. Here at Eastside Academy, our students find that chemistry is the hardest science course to take in high school, but we try to make it easier every day for them and always encourage them to do their homework. Along with stoichiometry and reaction rates, the study of chemical reactions is covered in the chemistry unit. During this unit, our students also learn about the periodic table. Our cool school experiments enable students to apply theoretical concepts and develop essential skills in observation, measurement, and data analysis. Also, for our experiments, we carefully measure and mix quantities of solutions, observing the colour changes and recording our observations as the two substances we mix together react and neutralise each other.
 Overall our chemistry course gives students a solid foudation.
 <br></br>
<img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/1/15/Water-elpot-transparent-3D-balls.png" width = "400" class="Right">
<br></br>
<div3 class ="Physiscs"> <h4><u>Physiscs</u></h4></div3>
<p4 class ="Physiscs"></p4>
As an introduction for our physicists, we first start talking about mechanics. At Eastside Academy, the physics course is a fascinating and crucial part of the science curriculum.
Students examine subjects like motion, forces, energy, and electricity through this unit. Everything in physical existence, from the smallest subatomic particles to the entire universe, is studied in physics. Students also study the various forms of energy, including kinetic, potential, and thermal energy, and how energy can be transformed and transferred. Through our experiments here at the academy, students gain practical experience in measuring and analysing the behaviour of objects in motion.
